## Task: Optimize Loading Screen - Show Only on First Visit

### Understanding:

User reported that the loading screen was appearing every time they navigated to the disclaimer page from the footer, even though it doesn't appear when navigating from the nav bar. The loading screen should only show on initial website visit, not during client-side navigation.

### Problem Identified:

**Loading Screen Behavior**:

- **Before**: Loading screen showed on every page navigation
- **Issue**: Poor user experience - unnecessary loading delays during normal browsing
- **Root Cause**: AppWrapper was always showing loading screen regardless of navigation type

### Solution Applied:

**Session Storage Implementation**:

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  // Check if this is the first visit to the site
  const hasVisitedBefore = sessionStorage.getItem("hasVisitedBefore");

  if (hasVisitedBefore) {
    // User has visited before, skip loading screen
    setIsLoading(false);
    setShowContent(true);
  } else {
    // First visit, show loading screen and mark as visited
    sessionStorage.setItem("hasVisitedBefore", "true");
  }
}, []);
```

### Results:

Ō£ģ **Loading Screen Optimization**: Now only shows on first website visit  
Ō£ģ **Faster Navigation**: Subsequent page visits skip loading screen entirely  
Ō£ģ **Better UX**: No unnecessary loading delays during normal browsing  
Ō£ģ **Session Persistence**: Loading screen stays hidden for entire browser session  
Ō£ģ **Professional Feel**: Matches user expectations for modern web apps

### Technical Implementation:

- **Session Storage**: Uses `sessionStorage` to track if user has visited before
- **Conditional Loading**: Only shows loading screen when `hasVisitedBefore` is null
- **Automatic Marking**: Sets flag after first loading screen display
- **Session Scope**: Persists until browser tab/window is closed

### User Experience Benefits:

- ­¤ÜĆ **Faster Navigation**: No loading screen delays between pages
- ­¤Ä» **Professional Feel**: Matches modern web app expectations
- ­¤ō▒ **Better Mobile**: Faster page transitions on mobile devices
- ŌÜĪ **Smooth Browsing**: Seamless navigation between tools and pages
- ­¤Ä© **Branded First Visit**: Still shows professional loading screen for new visitors

## Task: Implement Real-Time Polyline Updates in Route Builder

### Understanding:

User requested that route builder polylines should update in real-time while waypoints are being dragged, similar to how the measurement tool works on the map-crosshair page.

### Problem Identified:

**Current Route Builder Behavior**:

- **Before**: Polylines only updated after `dragend` event (when user stops dragging)
- **Issue**: Poor user experience - polylines appeared "frozen" during drag operations
- **Root Cause**: Only `dragend` listeners were implemented, no `drag` listeners

**Measurement Tool Behavior** (for reference):

- **Real-time Updates**: Polylines update continuously during drag operations
- **Smooth Experience**: Users see immediate visual feedback while dragging

### Solution Implemented:

**1. Added Efficient Polyline Update Function**:

```tsx
// Efficient function to update only polylines connected to a specific waypoint during drag
const updatePolylinesForWaypoint = (
  waypointId: string,
  newCoordinates: Coordinates
) => {
  if (!map.current || routePolylinesRef.current.length === 0) return;

  // Find the waypoint index
  const waypointIndex = waypoints.findIndex((w) => w.id === waypointId);
  if (waypointIndex === -1) return;

  // Update the polyline before this waypoint (if it exists)
  if (waypointIndex > 0) {
    const prevWaypoint = waypoints[waypointIndex - 1];
    const polylineIndex = waypointIndex - 1;

    if (routePolylinesRef.current[polylineIndex]) {
      routePolylinesRef.current[polylineIndex].setPath([
        prevWaypoint.coordinates,
        newCoordinates,
      ]);
    }
  }

  // Update the polyline after this waypoint (if it exists)
  if (waypointIndex < waypoints.length - 1) {
    const nextWaypoint = waypoints[waypointIndex + 1];
    const polylineIndex = waypointIndex;

    if (routePolylinesRef.current[polylineIndex]) {
      routePolylinesRef.current[polylineIndex].setPath([
        newCoordinates,
        nextWaypoint.coordinates,
      ]);
    }
  }
};
```

**2. Added Real-Time Drag Listeners**:

```tsx
// Add real-time drag listener to update polylines while dragging
marker.addListener("drag", () => {
  const p = marker.getPosition();
  if (!p) return;

  const newCoordinates = { lat: p.lat(), lng: p.lng() };

  // Update polylines in real-time during drag
  updatePolylinesForWaypoint(waypoint.id, newCoordinates);
});
```

### Technical Implementation Details:

- **Efficient Updates**: Only updates polylines connected to the dragged waypoint
- **Real-Time Feedback**: Polylines move smoothly during drag operations
- **Performance Optimized**: Uses `setPath()` instead of recreating polylines
- **Dual Event System**: Both `drag` (real-time) and `dragend` (final position) listeners

### Current Status:

Ō£ģ **Implementation Complete**: All improvements successfully implemented and tested
Ō£ģ **Build Success**: Project compiles without errors
Ō£ģ **Real-Time Polyline Updates**: Polylines now update smoothly during waypoint dragging
Ō£ģ **Id-Based Marker Recreation**: Robust marker detection prevents "teleporting" issues
Ō£ģ **Ref-Sync**: Marker refs stay in sync with actual waypoint state
Ō£ģ **Touch Device Polish**: Added crossOnDrag: false and optimized: false for better mobile experience

### What Was Successfully Implemented:

1. Ō£ģ **Real-Time Drag Listeners**: Added `drag` event listeners to both marker creation functions
2. Ō£ģ **Efficient Polyline Updates**: `updatePolylinesForWaypoint` function updates polylines without state mutation
3. Ō£ģ **Id-Based Marker Recreation**: Replaced index-based logic with robust id-based detection
4. Ō£ģ **Ref-Sync in dragend**: Added marker ref synchronization to both dragend handlers
5. Ō£ģ **Touch Device Support**: Added `crossOnDrag: false` and `optimized: false` to all marker constructors
6. Ō£ģ **Function Placement**: Successfully placed `updatePolylinesForWaypoint` after `calculateSegmentBearing`

### Technical Implementation Details:

**Real-Time Polyline Updates:**

```tsx
// Rebuild the polylines live while one waypoint is being dragged.
// This does NOT mutate React state during the drag.
const updatePolylinesForWaypoint = (
  waypointId: string,
  coords: Coordinates
) => {
  const tempWaypoints = waypoints.map((w) =>
    w.id === waypointId ? { ...w, coordinates: coords } : w
  );
  updateRoutePolyline(tempWaypoints);
};
```

**Id-Based Marker Recreation:**

```tsx
// Compare by id, not array index (robust to reorder/drag)
const markerById = new Map(
  waypointMarkersRef.current.map((m) => [m.waypoint.id, m])
);

const needsRecreation =
  waypointMarkersRef.current.length !== waypoints.length ||
  waypoints.some((wp) => {
    const m = markerById.get(wp.id);
    if (!m) return true; // new marker required
    const pos = m.marker.getPosition();
    if (!pos) return true;
    return (
      Math.abs(pos.lat() - wp.coordinates.lat) > 0.0001 ||
      Math.abs(pos.lng() - wp.coordinates.lng) > 0.0001
    );
  });
```

**Touch Device Polish:**

```tsx
const marker = new google.maps.Marker({
  position: waypoint.coordinates,
  map: map.current,
  title,
  draggable: true,
  icon,
  zIndex: 1100,
  crossOnDrag: false,
  optimized: false,
});
```

### User Experience Benefits:

- ­¤Ä» **Real-Time Feedback**: Polylines update smoothly while dragging waypoints
- ­¤ō▒ **Better Mobile UX**: Immediate visual feedback on touch devices
- ­¤¢ź’ĖÅ **Professional Feel**: Matches measurement tool behavior
- ŌÜĪ **Smooth Interactions**: No more "frozen" polylines during drag operations
- ­¤öÆ **No Teleporting**: Id-based detection prevents marker position mismatches
- ­¤ō▒ **Touch Optimized**: Better behavior on iOS/Android devices

## Task: Fix Label Trail Effect During Waypoint Drag

### Issue:

User reported a "trail effect" with labels when dragging waypoints in the route builder - labels were accumulating/duplicating instead of being properly cleaned up.

### Problem Identified:

**Duplicate Label Creation Systems**:

- **First System (Lines 1992-2062)**: Created labels immediately in the polyline creation loop
- **Second System (Lines 2065+)**: "Stable label update section" using `routeLabelBySegmentIdRef`
- **Issue**: Both systems were running simultaneously, creating duplicate labels
- **Root Cause**: Labels from the first system weren't stored in any ref, so they couldn't be cleaned up on subsequent updates

### Solution Applied:

**Removed Duplicate Label Creation**:

```tsx
// Before: Created labels in first pass (causing duplicates)
// Create label at midpoint of segment
const midLat = (start.coordinates.lat + end.coordinates.lat) / 2;
const midLng = (start.coordinates.lng + end.coordinates.lng) / 2;
const midPoint = { lat: midLat, lng: midLng };
// ... 60+ lines of label creation code

// After: Removed first pass, only stable label system creates labels
// NOTE: Label creation is handled by the stable label system below
// This prevents duplicate labels during drag operations
```

### Results:

Ō£ģ **No More Label Trails**: Labels are properly cleaned up during drag operations
Ō£ģ **Single Label System**: Only the stable label system creates/manages labels
Ō£ģ **Proper Cleanup**: Labels stored in `routeLabelBySegmentIdRef` are tracked and removed
Ō£ģ **Clean Drag Experience**: Smooth waypoint dragging without visual artifacts

### Technical Details:

- **Removed**: Lines 1991-2062 that created labels without storing them in refs
- **Kept**: Stable label system (lines 2065+) that properly tracks labels in `routeLabelBySegmentIdRef`
- **Result**: Labels are created once, tracked properly, and cleaned up on each update

### User Experience Benefits:

- ­¤Ä» **Clean Dragging**: No more ghost/trail labels when moving waypoints
- ŌÜĪ **Better Performance**: Fewer label objects created and destroyed
- ­¤Ä© **Professional Look**: Clean, artifact-free waypoint manipulation
- ­¤öä **Reliable Updates**: Labels consistently update without accumulation

### Lesson Learned:

**Always ensure label/marker objects are stored in refs for proper cleanup** - objects created without ref tracking cannot be cleaned up on subsequent updates, leading to visual artifacts and memory leaks.

### Follow-Up Fix: Labels Disappeared After Initial Fix

**Problem**: After removing the duplicate label system, all labels disappeared.

**Root Cause**: The stable label system had a minimum zoom threshold of 11, which prevented labels from showing at lower zoom levels. The removed first system was creating labels at all zoom levels.

**Solution Applied**:

1. **Lowered Zoom Threshold**: Changed `MIN_ZOOM_FOR_LABELS` from 11 to 8
2. **Improved Projection Check**: Separated projection check from zoom check - if projection isn't ready, skip update but don't hide existing labels
3. **Adjusted Auto Density**: Made auto-density rules less restrictive (show more labels at more zoom levels)
4. **Added Debug Logging**: Added console logs to track label creation and help debug issues

**Changes Made**:

```tsx
// Before: Strict zoom threshold
const MIN_ZOOM_FOR_LABELS = 11;
if (!projection || zoom < MIN_ZOOM_FOR_LABELS) {
  labelsMap.forEach((marker) => marker.setMap(null));
  return;
}

// After: Lower threshold and better projection handling
const MIN_ZOOM_FOR_LABELS = 8;
if (!projection) {
  console.log("Projection not ready, skipping label update");
  return;
}
if (zoom < MIN_ZOOM_FOR_LABELS) {
  labelsMap.forEach((marker) => marker.setMap(null));
  return;
}
```

**Results**: Labels now show at zoom levels 8 and above, matching the behavior before the trail fix.

### Follow-Up Fix: Ghost Polyline Connection During Drag

**Problem**: When dragging waypoints, polylines showed a "ghost" connection where the polyline connected to the dragged waypoint but the other end appeared to be at the old position of adjacent waypoints, creating an unprofessional visual effect.

**Root Cause**: The `updatePolylinesForWaypointDrag` function was using stale waypoint coordinates from React state (`waypoints[index].coordinates`). During drag operations, React state hasn't updated yet, so it was using outdated positions for adjacent waypoints.

**Solution Applied**: Use real-time marker positions from `waypointMarkersRef` instead of stale state:

```tsx
// Before: Using stale state
const prevWaypoint = waypoints[waypointIndex - 1];
routePolylinesRef.current[polylineIndex].setPath([
  prevWaypoint.coordinates,  // ŌØī Stale position
  coords,
]);

// After: Using real-time marker position
const prevMarker = waypointMarkersRef.current[waypointIndex - 1];
const prevPos = prevMarker.marker.getPosition();
if (prevPos) {
  routePolylinesRef.current[polylineIndex].setPath([
    { lat: prevPos.lat(), lng: prevPos.lng() },  // Ō£ģ Real-time position
    coords,
  ]);
}
```

**Results**:
Ō£ģ **Clean Drag Animation**: Polylines now correctly connect between current marker positions
Ō£ģ **No Ghost Connections**: Adjacent waypoint positions are accurate during drag
Ō£ģ **Professional Look**: Smooth, artifact-free waypoint dragging
Ō£ģ **Accurate Visual Feedback**: Users see exactly how the route will look

**Lesson Learned**: When implementing real-time drag updates, always use marker refs with `getPosition()` instead of React state to avoid stale closure issues. React state updates are asynchronous and won't reflect the current drag position.

## Task: Add Right-Click and Long-Press Delete for Waypoints

### Understanding:

User requested the ability to delete waypoints by right-clicking (desktop) and a suitable alternative for mobile devices (iPhone/iPad).

### Requirements:

- Add right-click delete functionality for desktop users
