### Features Implemented:

**1. Formatting Functions (lib/route-utils.ts):**

```tsx
// Format distance with specific unit
export function formatDistanceWithUnit(
  meters: number,
  unit: "nm" | "km" | "mi" | "m"
): string {
  switch (unit) {
    case "nm": // Nautical miles (maritime standard)
    case "km": // Kilometers (metric)
    case "mi": // Statute miles (imperial)
    case "m":  // Meters (precision)
  }
}

// Format bearing with different formats
export function formatBearing(
  bearing: number,
  format: "true" | "magnetic" | "both",
  magneticVariation: number = 0
): string {
  switch (format) {
    case "true":     // 123┬░T
    case "magnetic": // 125┬░M
    case "both":     // 123┬░T/125┬░M
  }
}
```

**2. AppBar Selectors:**

```tsx
{/* Distance Unit Selector */}
<Select value={distanceUnit} onValueChange={setDistanceUnit}>
  <SelectTrigger className="h-8 w-[80px]" title="Distance unit">
    <Ruler className="w-3 h-3" />
  </SelectTrigger>
  <SelectContent>
    <SelectItem value="nm">nm</SelectItem>
    <SelectItem value="km">km</SelectItem>
    <SelectItem value="mi">mi</SelectItem>
    <SelectItem value="m">m</SelectItem>
  </SelectContent>
</Select>

{/* Bearing Format Selector */}
<Select value={bearingFormat} onValueChange={setBearingFormat}>
  <SelectTrigger className="h-8 w-[80px]" title="Bearing format">
    <Compass className="w-3 h-3" />
  </SelectTrigger>
  <SelectContent>
    <SelectItem value="true">True</SelectItem>
    <SelectItem value="magnetic">Magnetic</SelectItem>
    <SelectItem value="both">Both</SelectItem>
  </SelectContent>
</Select>
```

**3. Updated Label Creation:**

```tsx
const bearingText = formatBearing(bearing, bearingFormat, 0);
const distanceText = formatDistanceWithUnit(distance, distanceUnit);
labelText = `${distanceText} ŌĆó ${bearingText} ŌĆó ${timeText}`;
```

**4. Updated Route Statistics:**

- Waypoint panel statistics use formatDistanceWithUnit
- Mobile stats card uses formatDistanceWithUnit
- ETA calculations adjust based on selected distance unit

### Technical Implementation:

- **State Variables**: `distanceUnit` and `bearingFormat` in RouteBuilder component
- **AppBar Props**: Added to AppBar interface and component props
- **Debounce Dependencies**: Added distanceUnit and bearingFormat to label rebuild dependencies
- **Icons**: Ruler (distance) and Compass (bearing) from lucide-react

### User Experience Benefits:

- ­¤ōÅ **Flexible Units**: Choose the distance unit that makes sense for your use case
- ­¤¦Ł **Bearing Options**: True for navigation, magnetic for field use, both for comparison
- ­¤īŹ **International**: Metric (km/m) and imperial (mi) options alongside nautical (nm)
- ŌÜĪ **Real-Time Updates**: Labels and statistics update immediately when format changes
- ­¤Ä» **Professional**: Icons make format selectors easy to identify and use

### Distance Unit Options:

- **nm (Nautical Miles)**: Default, maritime standard, 1 nm = 1852m
- **km (Kilometers)**: Metric standard, 1 km = 1000m
- **mi (Statute Miles)**: Imperial standard, 1 mi = 1609.34m
- **m (Meters)**: Precision measurements

### Bearing Format Options:

- **True (┬░T)**: Default, relative to true north (geographic)
- **Magnetic (┬░M)**: Relative to magnetic north (with magnetic variation)
- **Both (┬░T/┬░M)**: Show both true and magnetic bearings

### Future Enhancements:

- **Magnetic Variation**: Currently set to 0, could be calculated based on location using World Magnetic Model
- **Auto-Unit**: Could automatically select best unit based on distance (e.g., meters for < 1km)
- **Speed Unit**: Could add speed unit selector (kn/km/h/mph) to match distance unit

### Files Modified:

1. `lib/route-utils.ts` - Added formatDistanceWithUnit and formatBearing functions
2. `components/route-builder.tsx` - Added state variables, selectors, and updated all distance/bearing displays
3. `.cursorrules` - Documented implementation

### Lesson Learned:

**Provide user control over formatting** - Different users have different preferences and use cases. Maritime users prefer nautical miles and true bearings, land users prefer kilometers or statute miles, pilots may need magnetic bearings. Giving users format control makes the tool more versatile and professional.

## Task: Make Map-Based Tools Full-Screen Without Scrolling

### Understanding:

User requested that map-based tools (map crosshair and route builder) should position themselves so the map is immediately visible without requiring users to scroll down. This should work across mobile, tablet, and desktop devices.

### Problem Identified:

Both map-based tool pages had:
1. **Top padding**: `pt-20 sm:pt-24 lg:pt-28` pushing content below the fold
2. **Additional header content**: Titles, descriptions, and navigation taking up space above the map
3. **Limited map height**: Fixed heights (500px, 600px) instead of full viewport
4. **User friction**: Users had to scroll to see the map, especially on mobile devices

### Solution Applied:

**Map Crosshair Page (`/tools/map-crosshair`):**
- Changed from padded container to full-screen layout: `h-screen w-full overflow-hidden`
- Removed top padding and centered wrapper
- Made map use full viewport height: `height="100vh"`
- Moved navigation buttons to floating overlay at top center with backdrop blur
- Added proper z-index layering: `z-50` for navigation, map below

**Route Builder Page (`/tools/route-builder`):**
- Changed to full-screen layout: `h-screen w-full overflow-hidden`
- Removed all page padding and header content (title, description, usage instructions)
- Made route builder component use full viewport: `height="100vh"`
- Moved navigation to floating buttons at top-left with backdrop blur
- Added responsive text: "Back to Tools" on desktop, "Back" on mobile
- Removed redundant content since route builder has its own internal controls

### Technical Implementation:

**Map Crosshair Page:**
```tsx
<main className="relative h-screen w-full overflow-hidden">
  {/* Floating Navigation Header */}
  <div className="absolute top-3 left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 z-50 flex gap-2">
    <Button className="bg-black/60 backdrop-blur-sm ... shadow-lg">
      <Navigation className="w-4 h-4" />
      Standard Converter
    </Button>
    {/* ... */}
  </div>

  {/* Full-screen Map */}
  <GoogleMapsCrosshairWrapper height="100vh" {...props} />
</main>
```

**Route Builder Page:**
```tsx
<main className="relative h-screen w-full overflow-hidden">
  {/* Floating Navigation - Top Left */}
  <div className="absolute top-3 left-3 z-50 flex gap-2">
    <Button className="bg-black/60 backdrop-blur-sm ... shadow-lg">
      <ArrowLeft className="w-4 h-4 mr-2" />
      <span className="hidden sm:inline">Back to Tools</span>
      <span className="sm:hidden">Back</span>
    </Button>
    {/* ... */}
  </div>

  {/* Full-screen Route Builder */}
  <RouteBuilder height="100vh" {...props} />
</main>
```

### Results:

Ō£ģ **No Scrolling Required**: Maps are immediately visible on page load
Ō£ģ **Full Viewport Coverage**: Maps use entire screen height (100vh)
Ō£ģ **Floating Navigation**: Controls overlay the map with backdrop blur
Ō£ģ **Responsive Text**: Mobile-friendly button labels
Ō£ģ **Professional Look**: Clean, focused interface with shadow effects
Ō£ģ **Cross-Device**: Works perfectly on mobile, tablet, and desktop

### User Experience Benefits:

- ­¤ō▒ **Mobile Optimized**: No wasted screen space, immediate map interaction
- ­¤¢ź’ĖÅ **Desktop Friendly**: Full-screen professional mapping experience
- ŌÜĪ **Instant Access**: Users can start using the map immediately
- ­¤Ä© **Clean Design**: Floating controls don't obstruct map content
- ­¤Ä» **Focused Experience**: Removes distractions, emphasizes the map

### Files Modified:

1. `app/tools/map-crosshair/page.tsx` - Full-screen layout with floating navigation
2. `app/tools/route-builder/page.tsx` - Full-screen layout, removed header content
3. `.cursorrules` - Documented implementation

### Lesson Learned:

**Map-based tools should be full-screen by default** - When the primary interface is a map, don't waste valuable viewport space with headers and padding. Use floating overlays for navigation and controls. This is especially critical on mobile devices where screen real estate is limited. Users expect map tools to work like Google Maps or other professional mapping applications - full-screen and immediately accessible.
